<HEADLINE>
'MAJOR BREAKTHROUGH' EXPECTED ON OPENING TO CHINESE TOURISTS:
MOTC
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,   Jan.   15   (CNA) 01/15/07  15:52:36 (By Lilian Wu)
</P>
<P>
Minister  of Transportation  and Communications Tsai Duei said
Monday that there will be a "major breakthrough" this year in the
planned full opening of Taiwan to Chinese tourists coming to the
country for sightseeing trips.
</P>
<P>
Tsai made the remarks during a gathering with domestic media.
</P>
<P>
He noted that a full opening has been an established policy since
2004, adding that negotiations between the Taiwan Strait Tourism
Association and its Chinese counterpart, the Cross-Strait Tourism
Exchange Association -- the two bodies designated by their
respective governments to coordinate on the matter last year --
have made progress.
</P>
<P>
On whether the breakthrough will come after the Chinese New Year,
which falls on Feb. 18, Tsai only said that when the time is
ripe, the government will announce it.
</P>
